{"query": "How do the effects of growing cover crops between crop rows compare to growing them when a field is empty?", "summary": "Cover crops grown between crop rows (living mulches) and cover crops grown in empty fields (winter cover crops during fallow periods) show distinct differences in their effects. Cover crops between rows increase bacterial numbers and activity, reduce erosion, and show mixed effects on soil organic matter (Action 897). However, they can negatively impact pest regulation, with fewer aphids being parasitized and more aphids found in some comparisons when grown between broccoli plants (Action 1394). In vineyards and orchards, ground cover between rows generally shows similar grape yields compared to bare soil, though two studies found lower grape yields with grass between vine rows (Action 1352).

Cover crops in empty fields during winter periods demonstrate more consistent benefits for soil health. They increase soil organic matter in most studies, with one meta-analysis and ten controlled studies showing more organic matter in soils with winter cover crops (Action 1345). These winter cover crops increase nitrogen availability in soils, with ten studies showing more nitrogen compared to soils without them (Action 1345). They enhance microbial biomass, with five studies finding more microbial biomass in soils with cover crops (Action 1345). Winter cover crops also improve water management by reducing nitrate leaching, with four studies showing less nitrate leached from soils with winter cover crops compared to those without (Action 1357). They reduce soil erosion, with two controlled studies finding less erosion compared to fallows or bare soils (Action 1345).

Regarding cash crop yields, winter cover crops show variable effects, with studies finding sometimes higher, sometimes lower, and sometimes no differences in yields compared to plots without cover crops (Action 1351). The choice of cover crop species matters, with eight studies showing higher cash crop yields when legumes were used as winter cover crops compared to non-legumes (Action 1351).", "action_ids": ["897","1351","1352","1357","1394","1345"]}
